# Klawock

If you're here to learn about Klawock, Alaska, try to keep up. It's a [city](/City_(Alaska)) that exists, apparently, in the [Prince of Wales–Hyder Census Area](/Prince_of_Wales%E2%80%93Hyder_Census_Area,_Alaska), within the U.S. state of [Alaska](/Alaska). Specifically, it's perched rather precariously on the west coast of [Prince of Wales Island](/Prince_of_Wales_Island_(Alaska)), overlooking the Klawock Inlet, with Klawock Island itself providing a somewhat less interesting backdrop. Its [Tlingit](/Tlingit_language) name, Lawáak, rolls off the tongue with a certain gravitas, unlike some of the administrative titles it's accumulated over the centuries.

The city, with coordinates precisely pinned at 55°33′18″N 133°05′07″W / 55.55500°N 133.08528°W, currently hosts a population of 720 residents, as recorded in the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census). This figure represents a slight, almost imperceptible dip from the 755 recorded a decade prior in the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_Census), and a more noticeable decline from the 854 counted in 2000. It's not exactly a bustling metropolis, but then again, one rarely seeks out bustling metropolises in this corner of the world. For those attempting to navigate their way here, Klawock lies approximately 90 kilometres (56 mi) southwest of [Ketchikan](/Ketchikan,_Alaska), a mere 11 kilometres (6.8 mi) from [Craig](/Craig,_Alaska), and about 39 kilometres (24 mi) overland from [Hollis](/Hollis,_Alaska).

The community holds the rather quaint, if not entirely self-congratulatory, nickname "Site of the First Salmon Cannery in Alaska." Its motto, "kla-na-kee-duk," is perhaps best left to those who understand its local significance.

